    <!--                  SECTION THREE: PARALLEL LINES                  -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDef_9">• Parallel lines never meet.
\n • A transversal cuts two lines at different points.
\n • Creates alternate and corresponding angles.</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefQuestion_9">Do parallel lines ever intersect?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerOne_9">True</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerTwo_9">False</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefAnswerThree_9"></string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_9">False</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryProperties_9">• Through a point, one parallel can be drawn to a line.
\n • Lines parallel to the same line are also parallel.
\n • In a triangle, angles sum to 180°; polygon sums follow 180°×(n−2).</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsQuestion_9">What is the sum of the interior angles of a triangle (in degrees)?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerOne_9">90</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_9">180</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsAnswerThree_9">360</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_9">180</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExamples_9">• Given two lines cut by a transversal, if the alternate interior angles are equal (e.g. both 55°), then the two lines are parallel by the alternate angles criterion.
\n • To prove the triangle angle sum: draw a line through vertex C parallel to side AB. The alternate angles show that the three angles at C together form a straight angle of 180°, proving angle A + angle B + angle C = 180°.
\n • The exterior angle at C equals the sum of the two non-adjacent interior angles A and B, confirming the exterior angle theorem.</string>

    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExQuestion_9">How many lines parallel to a given line can be drawn through a point not on that line?</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_9">1</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_9">2</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_9">3</string>
    <string name="SectionThreeTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_9">1</string>

