    <!--                  SECTION FOUR: QUADRILATERALS                   -->
    <!-- ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ -->

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDef_9">• Parallelogram has opposite sides parallel.
\n • Rectangle, rhombus, and square are special cases.
\n • Trapezoid has one pair of parallel sides.</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefQuestion_9">How many pairs of parallel sides does a parallelogram have?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerOne_9">1</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerTwo_9">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefAnswerThree_9">3</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryDefCorrectAnswer_9">2</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryProperties_9">• Parallelogram sides and angles are equal.
\n • Rhombus diagonals are perpendicular and bisect angles.
\n • Triangle and trapezoid midlines are parallel and half-lengths.</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsQuestion_9">Are the diagonals of a rhombus perpendicular to each other?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerOne_9">True</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerTwo_9">False</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsAnswerThree_9"></string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryPropsCorrectAnswer_9">True</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExamples_9">• In parallelogram ABCD, draw diagonal AC. Triangles ABC and CDA are congruent by ASA (alternate angles and shared diagonal), so AB = CD and BC = DA, proving opposite sides are equal.
\n • To divide segment AB into 3 equal parts using Thales theorem: draw a ray from A at any angle, mark 3 equal steps (using a compass) to get points P1, P2, P3. Connect P3 to B, then draw parallels through P1 and P2 to divide AB in ratio 1:1:1.
\n • The diagonal of a parallelogram divides it into 2 congruent triangles, which confirms that opposite sides and opposite angles are equal.</string>

    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExQuestion_9">Into how many congruent triangles does one diagonal divide a parallelogram?</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerOne_9">1</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerTwo_9">2</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExAnswerThree_9">4</string>
    <string name="SectionFourTheoryWorkedExCorrectAnswer_9">2</string>

